V) to public policy debates, academic disputes, and technology industries. Outlining how postrace ideologies confound struggles for racial justice and equality, the contributors open up new critical avenues for understanding the powerful cultural, discursive, and material conditions that render postrace the racial project of our time.Contributors. Inna Arzumanova, Sarah Banet-Weiser, Aymer Jean Christian, Kevin Fellezs, Roderick A. Ferguson, Herman Gray, Eva C. Hageman, Daniel Martinez HoSang, Victoria E. Johnson, Joseph Lowndes, Roopali Mukherjee, Safiya Umoja Noble, Radhika Parameswaran, Sarah T. Roberts, Catherine R. Squires, Brandi Thompson Summers, Karen Tongson, Cynthia A. Young  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aEthnicityzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aEthnicityzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aPost-racialismzUnited States. 0aRace awarenesszUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBanet-Weiser, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGray, Herman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMukherjee, Roopali, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478003250zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478003250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478003250.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles